---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — Crontinel"
  description="Crontinel is built by Harun R Rayhan, a software engineer who got burned by silent cron failures one too many times."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-16">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-8">About Crontinel</h1>

    <div class="space-y-6 text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">

      <p>
        Crontinel started with a familiar story: a <code class="text-gray-300 bg-gray-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">send-invoices</code> job
        silently failed for three days. No alert. No error. Customers didn't get invoices.
        The generic cron monitor showed green the whole time because the scheduler
        was technically still running, just not doing anything useful.
      </p>

      <p>
        The root cause was a Horizon supervisor that had crashed. Horizon itself reported
        "running." The supervisor that processed the <code class="text-gray-300 bg-gray-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">billing</code> queue
        was not. There was no tool that could tell you that from the outside.
      </p>

      <p>
        Crontinel was built to fix that gap. It reads Horizon's Redis keys directly, the same data the Horizon dashboard shows you, and turns it into configurable
        alerts. It also hooks into Laravel's scheduler events to record every cron run
        with its exit code and duration, so you can see exactly what ran, when, and whether it succeeded.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-white font-semibold text-base pt-4">Why not use existing tools?</h2>

      <p>
        Cronitor, Healthchecks.io, and similar services check whether something pinged them on time. That model works if your only concern is "did the scheduler run?" It does not tell you whether the jobs the scheduler dispatched were actually processed, whether Horizon is paused, or whether a specific queue has 2,000 jobs sitting unprocessed. They see what your app reports; Crontinel reads what your app is actually doing.
      </p>

      <p>
        Datadog and other APM tools can instrument queue workers with enough configuration, but they are general-purpose platforms built around traces and metrics. Setting up queue depth alerts in Datadog means writing custom metrics pipelines, managing agents, and paying for ingestion at a scale that rarely makes sense for a single Laravel app. Crontinel is purpose-built: install one package, get a working dashboard.
      </p>

      <p>
        The gap these tools leave is not a monitoring gap, it is a Laravel internals gap. None of them understand what <code class="text-gray-300 bg-gray-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">horizon:supervisor</code> keys in Redis mean, or that a scheduler firing does not guarantee a job was processed. Crontinel was built specifically to close that gap.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-white font-semibold text-base pt-4">Open source first</h2>

      <p>
        The core package is MIT licensed and free forever. Install it in 2 commands,
        get a dark dashboard at <code class="text-gray-300 bg-gray-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">/crontinel</code>,
        and configure Slack or email alerts in your <code class="text-gray-300 bg-gray-900 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs">.env</code>.
        No SaaS required.
      </p>

      <p>
        The hosted SaaS adds multi-app dashboards, longer history retention, team access,
        and a REST API. It's for teams who manage more than one Laravel app and want
        a single pane of glass without running their own infrastructure.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-white font-semibold text-base pt-4">Built by</h2>

      <p>
        <a href="https://github.com/HarunRRayhan" class="text-gray-300 hover:text-white underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Harun R Rayhan</a>
        , a software engineer with 17 years in backend and cloud infrastructure.
        AWS, Laravel, DevOps. Building developer tools that solve real problems.
      </p>

      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 pt-4">
        <a
          href="https://github.com/crontinel/crontinel"
          class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-white transition-colors flex items-center gap-2"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
        >
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M12 0C5.37 0 0 5.37 0 12c0 5.31 3.435 9.795 8.205 11.385.6.105.825-.255.825-.57 0-.285-.015-1.23-.015-2.235-3.015.555-3.795-.735-4.035-1.41-.135-.345-.72-1.41-1.23-1.695-.42-.225-1.02-.78-.015-.795.945-.015 1.62.87 1.845 1.23 1.08 1.815 2.805 1.305 3.495.99.105-.78.42-1.305.765-1.605-2.67-.3-5.46-1.335-5.46-5.925 0-1.305.465-2.385 1.23-3.225-.12-.3-.54-1.53.12-3.18 0 0 1.005-.315 3.3 1.23.96-.27 1.98-.405 3-.405s2.04.135 3 .405c2.295-1.56 3.3-1.23 3.3-1.23.66 1.65.24 2.88.12 3.18.765.84 1.23 1.905 1.23 3.225 0 4.605-2.805 5.625-5.475 5.925.435.375.81 1.095.81 2.22 0 1.605-.015 2.895-.015 3.3 0 .315.225.69.825.57A12.02 12.02 0 0024 12c0-6.63-5.37-12-12-12z"/>
          </svg>
          GitHub
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://x.com/HarunRRayhan"
          class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-white transition-colors"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
        >
          X / Twitter
        </a>
        <a
          href="mailto:support@crontinel.com"
          class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-white transition-colors"
        >
          Email
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
